const EXTRACT_06_DYSTOPIAN = `The siren sounded at six, as it always did, and the city woke in unison. Not gradually, not with the slow unfurling of consciousness that Mara's grandmother had once described - the lazy stretch, the warm confusion of dreams dissolving - but all at once, every citizen rising from their regulation cots at the same mechanical instant, feet hitting cold concrete floors in a single synchronised beat that echoed through the tower blocks like a collective heartbeat.

Mara dressed in the grey coveralls that hung from the hook beside her bed. Size 3, Category B, Sector 7. The fabric was stiff and smelled of the chemical wash that stripped out all trace of individuality - no perfume, no sweat, no human scent of any kind. She caught a glimpse of herself in the small square of polished metal that served as a mirror: pale face, cropped hair, eyes that had learned long ago not to betray what lay behind them.

In the corridor, the others moved in silence. Doors opened and closed with practised efficiency. No one spoke before the Morning Address - that was Article 14 of the Compliance Code, and violations were logged automatically by the sensors embedded in every wall, every ceiling, every surface that the Administration's cameras could not reach. The sensors listened for whispers. They measured the frequency of breathing. They could detect, so the rumours said, the electrical signature of a lie.

Mara walked with her head down, matching the pace of those around her, but inside her chest something was happening that no sensor had yet learned to read. It was small and dangerous, a flame cupped against the wind. It was the thing her grandmother had called, in the old language that no one was permitted to speak any more, hope.`

