const EXTRACT_07_CRIME = `Detective Sergeant Carla Voss stood at the edge of the canal and looked down at the water. It was the colour of cold tea, opaque and still, reflecting nothing but the underside of the bridge and a strip of grey November sky. Somewhere beneath that surface lay the answer to a question she had been asking for eleven days, and the thought of it made her stomach tighten.

"Anything?" she asked, without turning around.

Behind her, the forensic team moved with the quiet precision of people who understood that haste was the enemy of truth. Their white suits made them look clinical, alien, out of place against the crumbling brickwork and rusted iron of the old towpath. PC Brennan, the youngest on the team, was photographing tyre tracks in the mud with the kind of concentration that only the very new or the very frightened could sustain.

"Boot print," he said. "Size nine or ten. Recent - last forty-eight hours, maybe less."

Carla nodded but did not write it down. She had learned, over twenty-three years of this work, that the obvious evidence was rarely the important evidence. The boot print would be catalogued, measured, cross-referenced, and it would tell them something - but it would not tell them the thing that mattered. The thing that mattered was always in the margins: the detail that didn't fit, the absence where something should have been, the silence that was louder than any confession.

She crouched at the water's edge and studied the bank. The reeds had been flattened in a line approximately two metres wide, leading from the towpath to the water. Something - or someone - had been dragged. The mud was gouged in parallel tracks, deep and deliberate, and at the waterline itself there was a smear of something dark that could have been oil, could have been blood, could have been nothing at all.

"Get lights on the water," she said quietly. "And call the divers."

She stood and brushed the mud from her knees. Across the canal, in the window of a converted warehouse apartment, a curtain moved.`

