const EXTRACT_09_HISTORICAL = `The letter arrived on a Tuesday, carried across three hundred miles of war-torn countryside by a boy on a horse who could not have been more than fourteen. Thomas watched him ride up the lane from the forge, where he had been hammering a ploughshare into something that was not a ploughshare but which the requisition officer would record as one when he came on Thursday. The boy's horse was lathered and thin, its ribs showing like the hull of an unfinished boat, and when the boy dismounted he stumbled and had to grip the gatepost to stay upright.

"Message for Thomas Hartley," the boy said, holding out a folded paper sealed with wax the colour of dried blood. His voice cracked on the surname. He was trying very hard to be a soldier, Thomas could see - trying to hold his narrow shoulders straight, to keep his chin raised, to look a man of forty-seven in the eye without flinching. But his hands shook, and there was mud on his cheek, and his uniform had been made for someone with broader arms.

Thomas took the letter. He did not open it. He knew, with the particular certainty of a man who had already received two such letters in two years, what it would contain: a date, a place, a name. The date would be recent. The place would be somewhere he had never been and could not picture. The name would be his son's.

He invited the boy inside and set bread and cheese before him, and a cup of ale that he could ill afford to spare. The boy ate with the desperate efficiency of someone who had not seen food in a day or more, tearing the bread with both hands, barely chewing. Thomas sat across from him at the kitchen table and watched, and thought about what it meant to live in a country that sent its children to deliver news of its children's deaths.

The letter lay on the table between them, unopened. The wax seal caught the light from the window, and for a moment it looked like a wound - a small, perfect circle of red against the pale paper. Thomas placed his hand over it, not to open it, but to hold it still. As if the words inside might escape if he did not keep them contained.

Outside, a blackbird sang in the apple tree. The forge was cooling. The thing that was not a ploughshare sat on the anvil, half-finished, waiting for a purpose that no one would ever speak aloud.`

