              'Grade 4-5':
                'The writer makes the experience of hearing colours vivid by comparing each colour to a different type of music. The blue sky is described as "an orchestra, vast and layered" which suggests it is complex and beautiful. The yellow corn is "a chorus of children singing slightly out of tune," which sounds happy but imperfect. The green hills produce "a hymn so ancient that Rosa felt it in her bones," which suggests something deep and spiritual. The structure moves through the colours one by one, getting more powerful each time, which shows how the experience is growing stronger.',
              'Grade 6-7':
                'The writer presents the synaesthetic experience through an extended conceit in which colour becomes music, creating a hierarchical taxonomy of sensory perception. The blue sky is "an orchestra, vast and layered," a metaphor that implies complexity, harmony, and composed intentionality - the sky as deliberate artistic creation. The modifying clause "with high bright notes where the light was strongest and deep, slow movements where the clouds gathered" maps musical dynamics onto meteorological variation, making weather and music structurally equivalent. Yellow is presented as less controlled: "a chorus of children singing slightly out of tune" - the qualifying "slightly" is crucial, introducing imperfection as a form of authenticity. Green represents the deepest register: the hymn is "so ancient that Rosa felt it in her bones rather than her ears," a phrase that relocates perception from the auditory to the somatic, suggesting that the most fundamental colours bypass the senses entirely and communicate directly with the body. Structurally, the paragraph moves from sky to earth, from orchestra to hymn, from hearing to feeling - a descent that is also a deepening.',
              'Grade 8-9':
                'The writer constructs a phenomenology of synaesthesia in which the dissolution of sensory boundaries becomes a metaphor for approaching death - and, paradoxically, for experiencing life more fully than ever before. The paragraph\'s structure is architectonic: blue (sky/orchestra) is the widest, most public sound; yellow (corn/children) is communal but imperfect; green (hills/hymn) is geological, predating not merely music but "language" and "everything except the earth itself." This tripartite descent from cultural to natural to primordial sound enacts a progressive stripping-away of human constructs, as though Rosa\'s approaching death is granting her access to frequencies that civilisation obscures. The musical metaphors are precisely calibrated: an "orchestra" implies human composition, a "chorus" implies collective but organic voice, a "hymn" implies something between human and divine - the progression moves steadily from the made to the given. The qualification of yellow as "slightly out of tune" is the paragraph\'s most human moment, its imperfection functioning as an emblem of mortal beauty. The shift from "ears" to "bones" in the green passage dissolves the body\'s perceptual hierarchy, suggesting that at the threshold of death, the distinction between perceiving and being dissolves.',
