              'Grade 4-5':
                'The writer shows the family\'s grief through the empty chair. The fact that "nobody moved it or spoke about it" tells us the family is avoiding their feelings. Grace sets three places at dinner and leaves the fourth "bare," which creates a sad contrast. The word "bare" makes the missing place feel very empty. The second paragraph describes Grace stirring sauce with a wooden spoon she has used "for fifteen years," which shows how their routines continue even though their family has changed. The description of watching the sauce so she does not have to "watch the clock" reveals that the routine is a way of avoiding painful thoughts.',
              'Grade 6-7':
                'The writer presents grief as a presence that manifests through domestic absence. The opening sentence - "The kitchen table had four chairs, but for the past seven months only three of them had been used" - deploys the adversative "but" to create a structural fracture: the table\'s physical completeness is contradicted by its functional incompleteness. The verb choices in the subsequent sentence - "nobody moved it or spoke about it or acknowledged" - form a tricolon of avoidance, each verb escalating from physical to verbal to psychological. The empty chair is not merely unused but actively maintained in its emptiness: it is "pushed in neatly," an adverb that implies care, even reverence. The father is introduced only through his absence and his habits - unfolding a newspaper, complaining "mildly and without real grievance" - and these remembered details are devastating because their ordinariness measures the scale of what has been lost. Grace\'s spoon, "its handle worn smooth by the repetitive grip of her fingers," is a synecdoche for the marriage: shaped by years of habitual contact, now reduced to solitary use. The structure of the second paragraph - from watching sauce to not watching the clock to not calculating hours - traces a chain of deliberate cognitive avoidance, each stage representing a deeper level of suppression.',
