                'I agree that Grace has conflicting emotions. She keeps the empty chair at the table, which shows she is holding on to her husband\'s memory, but she does not set a place for him, which shows she is also trying to accept his absence. When Sophie says the letter is "from Dad," Grace\'s wooden spoon stops, which is a physical sign of her shock. The description of his handwriting as something she "once found charming and now found unbearable" shows her feelings have changed. However, the phrase "not because she hated it but because she did not" tells us she still has feelings for him, which makes the situation more complicated. She places the letter "unopened, beside the sauce" which shows she is not ready to deal with it yet. Overall I agree that the tension between holding on and letting go is present throughout.',
              'Grade 6-7':
                'I agree that the extract is structured around emotional contradiction, though I would frame it more precisely: Grace is not struggling between holding on and letting go, but inhabiting a third state - the sustained practice of endurance, which is neither acceptance nor denial but something more complex. The opening paragraphs establish this through the management of the fourth chair: it is neither removed (which would be letting go) nor set for dinner (which would be holding on) but maintained in a state of curated emptiness. The letter\'s arrival disrupts this careful equilibrium. The moment when "the wooden spoon stopped" is the extract\'s structural pivot: it is an involuntary break in the rhythm of avoidance, the body betraying what the mind has disciplined. The description of Sophie holding the letter "like an offering, or a test, or a grenade with the pin already pulled" is a devastating tricolon that traces the letter\'s possible meanings from sacred to challenging to destructive. Grace\'s final assessment of the handwriting - unbearable "not because she hated it but because she did not" - is the extract\'s emotional thesis: the worst pain is not the pain of antipathy but the pain of persistent love for someone who has caused you to need this much armour. Placing the letter beside the sauce enacts the same management strategy as the empty chair: acknowledgement without engagement, proximity without intimacy.',
              'Grade 8-9':
                'The statement accurately identifies the central tension, but I would argue that the extract\'s most sophisticated achievement is its demonstration that "holding on" and "letting go" are not in fact opposites but different expressions of the same overwhelming love. Every action Grace performs is simultaneously both: the empty chair is held in place (holding on) and left unset (letting go); the routine of Thursday pasta preserves the family\'s structure (holding on) while accommodating the father\'s absence (letting go). The letter\'s arrival threatens to collapse this carefully maintained duality by demanding a definitive response. The somatic detail - the stopped spoon, the awareness of "every sound in the kitchen" - registers the moment when Grace\'s defensive system is breached: the hyper-perception of sound (refrigerator hum, clock tick, Sophie\'s breathing) suggests a consciousness suddenly and painfully open to the present, unable to maintain the selective attention that has been her survival mechanism. The extended simile describing Sophie holding the letter - "an offering, or a test, or a grenade" - is structurally ascending in violence, each comparison more destructive than the last, yet the child\'s gesture is physically identical in each reading: the meaning of the letter depends entirely on the emotional framework brought to it. The final sentence is the extract\'s masterpiece: Grace describes the handwriting as unbearable "not because she hated it but because she did not, and that distinction was the hardest thing she had ever had to carry." The syntactical negation - "not because... but because she did not" - forces the reader to hold two contradictory ideas simultaneously, enacting precisely the conflict the statement identifies. The verb "carry" is quietly perfect: it implies both burden and motion, weight and the refusal to set it down.',
